<div class='communityQuestionAndAnswer'>
<div class='communityQuestion'>
<div class='questionText'>
<a href="/questions/631393-in-the-intro-page-xvii-the-translator">In the intro (page xvii), the translator mentions that this work is preceded by The Aims of the Philosophers and The Standard for Knowledge, all dealing with the same subject of explaining and rebutting Avicenna. Would I gain better understanding if I read these other two works first before I go into Incoherence of Philosophers? Or is this book sufficient enough to be understood on its own?</a>
</div>
<div class='communityQAFooter questionFooter'>
<ul class='questionFooterActions'>
<li class='footerItem like'>
<span class='likeItContainer' id='like_container_community_question_631393'><a rel="nofollow" class="jsLike like_it" href="https://www.goodreads.com/user/new?remember=true&amp;return_url=%2Fbook%2Fshow%2F254522.The_Incoherence_of_the_Philosophers">like</a></span>

</li>
<li class='footerItem communityQuestionTimestamp'>
<a href="/questions/631393-in-the-intro-page-xvii-the-translator">5 years ago</a>
</li>
<li class='footerItem communityQuestionPermalink'>
<a href="/questions/631393-in-the-intro-page-xvii-the-translator">Add your answer</a>
</li>
</ul>
</div>

</div>
<div class='allCommunityAnswers'>
<div class='communityAnswer'>
<div class='communityAnswerBody'>
<div class='answererUserIcon'>
<a class="leftAlignedImage userPhoto" href="/user/show/42291993-muhammad-shehab"><img alt="" src="https://i.gr-assets.com/images/S/compressed.photo.goodreads.com/users/1429402929i/42291993._UX100_CR0,0,100,100_.jpg" /></a>
</div>
<div class='communityAnswerTextContainer'>
<span class='communityAnswererName'>
<a href="/user/show/42291993-muhammad-shehab">Muhammad Shehab</a>
</span>
<span class='communityAnswerText'>
<span class="expandableContainer"><span class="truncatedContent">u would if u read the 1st one (The Aims ...) 1st, Alghazali wrote this one as an introduction to the Incoherence, he wrote it as if he was one of them<a class="jsShow showAction" href="#">…more</a></span><span class="fullContent">u would if u read the 1st one (The Aims ...) 1st, Alghazali wrote this one as an introduction to the Incoherence, he wrote it as if he was one of them (philosophers) and he succeeded. And he wrote The Standard after he wrote The Incoherence so it would be explanation to logic which he used in the 1st 2 books. so u better read it as such:<br />1. The Aims of the Philosophers<br />2. The Incoherence of the Philosophers<br />3. The Standard for Knowledge (read it if u didn't fully understand logic in the 1st 2 books)<br /><br />and sorry my weak English :)<a class="jsHide hideAction" href="#">(less)</a></span></span>
</span>
</div>
